15.title: Agile content design
15.content:
Agile content design
Working in an agile team
Agile
 ways of working encourage teams to build quickly, test what they’ve built and iterate their work based on regular feedback and data.
Every product or service can vary, as can the team that delivers each stage.
As a content designer, the following information gives an idea of what you should be focusing on at each stage.
During discovery
To learn about your users, your subject and existing content:


find the words people use using Google Analytics, Adwords and Trends, online forums, social media 
attend user research - observe user research sessions and take notes, meet users, observe how they interact with current services 
find gaps or problems with existing content. Look at GOV.UK Feedex, helpline data and other existing feedback 
work with stakeholders, policy and subject matter experts to build your knowledge of the subject and understand the policy intent
review how existing content addresses user needs. Use GOV.UK, other online information, outbound letters and emails 
write problem statements, mission statements and service descriptions to help your team define their focus

During alpha
To build prototypes, design and iterate content:


create and update prototypes with other UCD team members. Use Figma, GOV.UK prototype kit, Visual studio code, Heroku and Git
write and test letters, text messages, emails and other notifications
follow GOV.UK and DfE design patterns and styles. Share new patterns and research with other designers in DfE and across government 
work with the digital communications team - DfE’s GOV.UK content team
design GOV.UK start and done pages and test with users 
test GOV.UK content with users to cover the whole journey 
work with legal and security to understand constraints on content 
share content and research for GOV.UK start, done and guidance pages to help business analysts and product owners to write clear user stories

During private beta
To design the content for your first release:


design error and validation messages 
show when the online service is unavailable 
explain how the service uses cookies and collects personal data 
write feedback questions to help the team learn about the user’s experience 
translate content into Welsh, if neccessary. The Welsh language team can give you this 
work with the digital communication team at DfE and the CDDO content team on GOV.UK start, done and guidance pages - for launch of public beta 
write metadata descriptions and keywords to help users find the right service and improve search engine rankings 
iterate content based on feedback from users, design hypotheses and analytics
help your team to name the service 

During live
To manage content:


continue to iterate the service content by using feedback and analytics to inform changes or discover new user needs to explore
regularly review and audit content to ensure it remains relevant, up-to-date and continues to meet users’ needs

16.title: Preparing for assessment
16.content:
Preparing for assessment
To have a successful assessment, you will need to show:


how you’ve mapped the user journeys in discovery
evidence of design options to test in alpha
how the design has been iterated based on research in beta 

You will also need to show:


how the product will meet user needs and business needs
the outcomes and how the product will deliver against these outcomes, in a sustainable and efficient way
how you’ve identified the most efficient and effective way to deliver the right information at the right time in a way that users need it. This design must be sustainable and cost efficient to answer business requirements and user needs

Talk about your service
During your assessment, tell the story about what you have done, instead of ticking off the standards one-by-one. Share what you have learnt and what you recommend for the next stage.
To prepare for this, look at the checklists for each stage to see if your team is we meeting the standards.
If your team is not meeting the standards, explain why. You should always present your evidence and recommendations clearly, even if this means your product may not move to the next stage.
All digital products with interactive or bespoke design should have some form of quality assurance. If your product is non-transactional and does not transfer data, then it will only need a peer review, rather than an assessment.
Find out more about service assessments.

         Content design
         Content design makes things easier for people to understand and use. Using data, research and testing to understand what people need and then design content to meet those needs. 
      
      
      
     
   

How we work
As content designers we focus on these GOV.UK Service S tandard points:


1. understand users and their needs
2. solve a whole problem for users

3. provide a joined up experience across all channels
4. make the service simple to use
5. make sure everyone can use the service
8. iterate and improve frequently
10. define what success looks like and publish performance data 
11. choose the right tools and technology

We work closely with the other user-centred design (UCD) professions
  on our team, including user research, service and interaction design, along with business analysts and developers to meet these standards.
How we meet the Service Standard
As a content design profession, we agree to:


evidence and document how we make design decisions (tools and evidence to back up content design decisions) 
ensure content is accessible (making your service accessible)
use the appropriate style and brand guide for the service or website
have a process in place to preview prior to publishing, such as a 2i, quality check and sign off content
work to a strategy, and publish a proposition statement - example for GOV.UK
where appropriate
test with users through user research and by building prototypes
work in collaboration with our user-centred design and policy colleagues to understand problems and create solutions
always develop content that meets user needs
set performance measures and monitor content against these measures (measuring success)
have a plan in place to continuously iterate and improve
work to the service manual standards
work to the GOV.UK proposition
, where applicable

We follow government guidance
As a starting point, we use:


Government Digital Service
(GDS) build platforms, products and services for government
Central Digital & Data Office
manage standards and service assessments for government. This includes the digital, data and technology function (DDaT) framework
GDS style guide
GDS content and publishing guidance
GDS Service Manual

We also follow DfE guidance
We use DfE specific guidance when considering things like tone of voice, specific styles and how to publish in DfE.
How to communicate
 is a section of our intranet that explains how we communicate at DfE, it includes:


working with strategic and digital communications teams
brand guidelines, including guidance on images and videos and document templates
DfE style guide
how to publish on GOV.UK
how to produce content for different channels, such as our blogs or presentation for internal and external use
make your content accessible

We have a DfE content strategy
 template, which should form the basis of individual product and service strategies.

79.content:

      Inclusive design
      Inclusive design aims to remove barriers that create extra effort for some groups of users, not just those with access needs and enables designers to draw on the full range of human diversity.
    
    
    
  


 
You may be assessed on how you’ve met this guidance at service assessments, through Service Standards 1. Understand users and their needs and 5. Make sure everyone can use the service
What inclusive design means
In short, inclusivity means design that is both representative and accessible.
If we use our own abilities and biases as a starting point, we end up with services designed for people of a specific gender, age, language ability, tech literacy, and physical ability.
Like accessibility, this includes individuals with physical or mental impairments, but it also goes much further than this. Inclusivity includes users of all ethnicities, backgrounds, gender, sexual orientation, and more into the user experience.


        
        
       Important: Tools and resources
        Use this online service to Estimate how many people using your website might be disabled. This will help you consider the types of people who may be using your service and who you should be testing with.
        
Writing inclusively
When we write, we may be introducing bias without realising it. We may also be using language that is gender specific when it shouldn’t be.
You can use the inclusivity settings in Office 365 to check the language of content in documents.


        
        
       Important: Enabling inclusivity checker in Office 365
        Go to: Editor > Settings > Inclusivity and tick the boxesThe spellchecker will now help you to start writing inclusive language and avoid any subconscious bias.
        
There’s no such thing as a ‘normal user’
The interactions we design with technology depend heavily on what we can see, hear, say, and touch.
Assuming all those senses and abilities are fully enabled all the time creates the potential to ignore many people who may have impairments with one or more of their senses.
Designing for inclusivity not only opens up Department for Education (DfE) services to more people with a wider range of abilities. It also reflects how people really are.
Recognise exclusion in design
Exclusion happens when we solve problems or design solutions using our own biases.
There are different ways someone can be excluded from using a service through disability and is dependent on the context of how people are using the service.
There are three types of exclusion designers must consider when designing services, components and features.
Temporary
Short term injury or context affects how users interact with the service. For example, having a broken arm may make it more difficult to use a phone, computer or mouse and keyboard.
Situational
The situation a user finds themself in might mean they cannot use the service at that moment in time. For example, being in a loud environment might make it difficult to hear or speak to someone on the phone if they need help using a service.
Permanent
Many people have a permanent disability and so designing for these users by default means the service will work for more people. For example, ensuring a service works with screen readers will work for a wide range of people.
Build knowledge in diversity
Do not rely solely on simulating different abilities. For example, using blindfolds, earplugs or putting one hand behind your back, test the service with a wide range of users.
Having empathy for your users and learning how people adapt in different ways to using the service, you can better understand how to design for a wide range of abilities.
Solve for one, works for all
Inclusive design means designing with consideration for many different circumstances.
However, ensuring the service works for blind users has the added benefit that it’ll work for users with temporary vision issues using voice over or a screen reader.
Additionally, someone who might find it easier to listen to guidance or content rather than read it if they are cooking dinner or out for a walk.
Find out more
The following links all open in a new tab.


Making your service more inclusive on GOV.UK
Inclusive Design Nielsen Norman Group
Inclusive Design Toolkit Microsoft

109.title: Types of prototyping
109.content:
Back to prototyping
Types of prototyping
We design and build prototypes to test solutions to problems.
Prototypes can be simple wireframe sketches, mockups through to low-code clickable prototypes using the GOV.UK prototype kit.


You can read more about prototyping and the differences between high and low fidelity prototypes on the Nielsen Normal Group (NNG) website.

How we do prototyping in DfE
We use differnet approaches to prototyping, depending on the audience, the complexity or what we want to test and find out. This means we could:


test simple sketches with pen and paper 
create realistic mockups and simple user journeys using Figma 
build clickable prototypes using the GOV.UK Prototype Kit which look and behave like real digital services

112.title: Prototype kit
112.content:
Back to prototyping
Prototype kit
Using the kit means you can build prototypes that look like a real GOV.UK service. This helps to make it easier to test for usability issues and get feedback on how the service might perform if it were a real service.


The prototype kit does not have production quality security measures so you must not use it for production-quality, or live, scenario testing.

The kit is used across Government and supported thorugh the cross-gov  #prototype-kit Slack channel.
Installing the kit
Follow the instructions to install prototype kit required software for Mac and Windows users.
There are tutorials and example code on the prototype kit website and you can make use of components and patterns from the GOV.UK Design System by copying HTML or Nunjucks code snippets into your prototype.
Branding your prototype
If your prototype is not intended for publishing to GOV.UK or service.gov.uk you should follow the branding your service guidance so that you do not cause confusion with your users.
Testing your prototype with users


  !
  
    Warning
    You must not use real user information or department data in any of your prototypes. Any display of information must be mock information. 
  

Depending on what testing you plan to do with users, you might want to run your prototype as a website, rather than on your local device.
We use Heroku to host prototypes and this is free for basic usage and sufficient for most prototype testing. You’ll need to create an account using your DfE email address.
You’ll also need a GitHub account to store your code and enable it to be deployed to Heroku.
Prototypes should be created in the GitHub DFE-Digital organisation, clearly identifying them as a prototype. You can request access to GitHub through Digital Tools support.


Full instructions on how to set up a Heroku account and deploy your prototype can be found on the publishing to Heroku guidance on the GOV.UK Design System.

      Component design
      Use the 4 stage acceptance criteria to validate if building a new component is the right thing to do.
    
    
    
  



When designing a new service, always start with what is available already.
Check the GOV.UK Design System (opens in new tab) before designing anything new because those patterns and components have already been researched and tested to make sure they’re accessible.

If you design anything new, your team will have to do all of the user research and accessibility testing and audit (opens in new tab) work to make sure that it is meeting the needs of your users and the accessibility standards.
You can also consider if there are components from design systems from other government departments (opens in new tab) that can support meeting your user needs.
Four stage acceptance criteria
This does not stop new components being created, but instead, puts checks in place to prevent over-engineering of service frontends.
Can the problem be solved with existing components or patterns?
The primary look and feel for digital services is the GOV.UK Frontend (opens in new tab) with available components, patterns and styles detailed in the GOV.UK Design System (opens in new tab).
Where appropriate, contributions should be made back to the design system to support the development of components for other users.
The GOV.UK Design System backlog (opens in new tab) also contains components which are being considered, are in development, or have been built by other designers.
If you decide the problem cannot be designed around by anything that exists in the design system, and it is a common problem, ask in DfE or Gov Digital Slack channels to see if anyone else has designed for the same problem.


interaction-design (DfE Slack)
developers (DfE Slack)
design (GOV Digital Slack) 
govuk-design-system (GOV Digital Slack)

Does it meet user needs across multiple services?
Designers can often work in silos and as a result aren’t aware of what other DfE designers are working on. This becomes obvious and a pain point for users of multiple DfE services, which have been designed and built by different teams.
Using components consistently, sharing with other designers and understanding who the users are and which services they use, helps to provide a consistent experience of DfE services and will help you meet the following standards:


 Service Standard 3 - provide a joined up experience across all channels (opens in new tab)
 WCAG 3.2.4 (AA) - Consistent identification (opens in new tab)

Does it add value to the user experience?
When designing a new component, you should ensure it meets a validated user need through user research. Designing components and features which meet user’s needs, should be shared so that other designers can use them in their services.
Components and features should not be built or designed just to make something look aesthetically pleasing, but instead add value, solve a problem or make something complex, understandable.
Is it accessible?
Accessibility is non-negotiable. New components or features must meet the component design guidelines and be able to be used by people of all abilities.
When considering a new component, it will often go through several iterations and design decisions will be made on what to take forward and what to discard, often through design crits, show and tells and user research.
Involving a wide range of people in these decisions will ensure you are being inclusive in your design approach.
You can read the full guidance for accessibility acceptance criteria for components on GOV.UK (opens in new tab)
Find out more
The following links open in a new tab


Designing for different browsers and devices
GOV.UK Frontend coding standards

Back to ways of working
Content design ways of working
Content audit
You should conduct content audits on a regular basis to ensure your content remains relevant and up to date. You can use this example audit (opens in new tab)
 to help.
To make sure that you do not create confusion for users or duplicate existing content you should always conduct an audit ahead of developing new content or at the point when you identify an upcoming change, for example a policy update or new financial details.
Content strategy
A content strategy should sit alongside your design history, service specific style guide and align to your product vision. It should focus on the users’ need for content in the service and should provide clear details on:


content development process
principles for content writing
content goals
user needs and outcomes
KPIs and metrics

The DfE has a content strategy (opens in new tab)
 that applies to all content the department publishes on GOV.UK and should also be applied to services and other digital products. If you do not have access to the DfE intranet, ask a colleague with access to get the information for you.
Quality checks
You should have an agreed and documented quality checking process.
Your process should be appropriate for your service and take into account different levels of changes, for example correcting a typing error vs updating a policy message.
Include how and when you will do things like:


2i review (second pair of eyes) and peer reviews
fact checking
policy sign-off
communicate the update with users

You should conduct your final quality checks of the content on a preview, displaying as it would appear once published.
Example workflow
The digital communications team (often referred to as DCT or digi comms) is an internal team that manage DfE’s content on GOV.UK.
You can use their clearance and 2i checklist to help develop your own. The following links will open in a new tab:


DCT’s GOV.UK clearance process
DCT’s 2i checklist

They are responsible for managing and publishing DfE content on GOV.UK. You will need to contact them to get a Start page for a service or a campaign sites.
You can get advice or make a content request through the DfE service portal (opens in new tab)
.
Monitoring
To deliver continuous improvement we:


monitor the performance of our content and services, this forms part of maintaining a sustainable service (opens in new tab)
set key performance indicators (KPIs) (opens in new tab)
and measure our content or service against those indicators on a regular basis
have a plan in place for how we will develop and test content through its life cycle
use Google Analytics, set up dashboards to measure against KPIs and set regular reports
build in ways for users to give feedback
identify ways to trigger alerts to issues with content and how to address them

Back to ways of working
Being an Interaction Designer
There’s more to being a designer than just the designing. we follow a number of techniques and approaches to become better designers.
What we do


Explore design solutions by understanding users, mapping journeys and creating prototypes
Test hypotheses and interactions which address user needs, behaviours and pain points
Feed into and support other disciplines and help to shape direction

What we don’t do


We do not build fully functional services to the GDS coding standard.

We use the prototyping kit to create prototypes for testing concepts.
Interaction designers are not developers. Our code is not to GDS coding standards and isn’t expected to be.
Prototypes are design artefacts, not an exact representation of the fully developed service. Links to databases, validation, error handling and everything functioning may not work.
We only prototype what’s needed for design and user testing.
As Designers
We:


follow GDS principles of how to be an Interaction Designer (opens new tab)
follow IxD team principles and good practice of how to do IxD
collaborate with each other
collaborate with other professions
work openly so we can be supported and can support others and reuse
reuse patterns for consistency between services
continually learn and develop

How we collaborate and work within teams
We:


share prototypes, journey maps and other IxD outputs
document design decisions (what and why)
do Collaborative Design Reviews and crits so we have awareness of work, can support each other and address differences between services
document Design Review outcomes for future reference
centralise shared documents and IxD outputs in a single location
maintain design histories and handover docs
share working boards, such as Lucid and Figma
feed new or iterated designs into the GDS community backlog
support delivery teams to track behaviours in the live code so we can learn and iterate future designs based on live usage

Back to ways of working
Joining user journeys between GOV.UK and digital services
To ensure a joined up journey for users between GOV.UK and DfE digital services, content designers work closely with the Digital Communications Team (DCT). The DCT create, publish and manage DfE’s content on GOV.UK.
Designing content for GOV.UK
When working with the DCT on DfE digital services, content designers:


must work with the DCT (opens intranet page in new tab) on any GOV.UK content. If you do not have access to the DfE intranet, ask a colleague with access to get the information for you
must prototype a version of any content as a minimum viable product (MVP) for non-transactional services on GOV.UK using Whitehall publisher (opens in new tab), the GOV.UK content management system
should map out journeys for services to show a user’s journey

Working in this way is part of how DfE content designers meet point 3 of the Service Standard to provide a joined up experience across all channels (opens in new tab).
Request a Whitehall publisher account
You will need a Whitehall publisher account to publish content on GOV.UK.
You can request access to Whitehall publisher training or accounts by raising a request with DCT (opens intranet page in new tab). If you’re a contractor you should ask a civil servant to make this request for you.
Providing a joined up experience across all channels
GOV.UK is a central publishing platform with services attached to it. Most users start their journey by reading some information before entering into a digital service. Content designers working on different parts of a journey should think about joined up services as users understand them, instead of as isolated transactions.
At DfE, DCT content designers generally work on GOV.UK content. Content designers working on a digital service that joins up to GOV.UK should work with DCT.
DCT use Whitehall publisher to manage DfE’s GOV.UK content. Other DfE content designers may be given access to Whitehall but they should follow the DfE GOV.UK content management process (opens intranet page in new tab) and work with them to publish any GOV.UK content.
Examples of joined up journeys between GOV.UK guidance and digital services


GOV.UK guidance for Get help with technology for remote education (opens in new tab) and the digital service Get help with technology (opens in new tab)
GOV.UK guidance for understanding Changes to the early years foundation stage (EYFS) framework (opens in new tab) and the digital information service Help for early years providers (opens in new tab)

Prototype non-transactional services using Whitehall
If you’re working on a non-transactional or information service at DfE, you must prototype a MVP version of this on GOV.UK using Whitehall publisher. You must work with DCT when you do this.
GOV.UK definition of a non-transactional service as something that:


uses interactivity to provide information with more specificity than static web pages. Content may also be interactive where there is dynamic delivery but where no information is stored or recorded. For example calculators, decision-trees and smart answers. This could also be called an interactive service as there is some interactivity though no actual transactions take place.

GOV.UK definition of an information service as something that:


provides users information in the form of guidance or marketing content. It may include dynamically-served content, content with data points included, or services that appear to the content consumer to be static pages but are aggregated by the CMS from content components. In other words, there is no opportunity for users to interact with the content other than to read it.

Map out your service journeys
You should map out journeys so that you understand a user’s navigation through a service, including which interactions happen outside of the service as part of completing a journey.
A service journey map creates a timeline of the user’s touchpoints. They’re useful for understanding where a user interacts with content and the different elements of a service that the content needs to be consistent with.
Mapping out journeys helps you understand the user’s steps and helps to create a consistent and smooth user journey between GOV.UK guidance and a digital service.
Even if you’re not using GOV.UK to create a digital service, you should try to include any GOV.UK guidance content that supports the service as part of user testing.
Read about why we use journey maps in government (opens in new tab).
There are different methods for creating user journey maps, read about how to make a user journey map (opens in new tab).
Work with DCT on GOV.UK content
You must work with DCT on any content planned for GOV.UK. If you’ve been given access to a Whitehall account, you’ll usually be able to buddy up with a DCT content designer to support you through to publishing.
If you’ve not been given a buddy, you should still be able to work with DCT by:


getting an induction from DCT
getting a 2i check from a DCT content designer before publishing
getting the right clearances

Buddy up on GOV.UK journeys
Buddying up is where a DCT content designer supports a DfE content designer through DCT publishing processes and collaborates on content design decisions.
Buddying up should be done when content designers are:


working on content that’s planned to go on GOV.UK 
testing content in Whitehall as part of checking whether an information service should be built that does not sit on GOV.UK

Get an induction from DCT if you’re using Whitehall
Get an induction from DCT if you’ve been given a Whitehall publisher account to work on GOV.UK content to get an overview of DfE processes for GOV.UK content, including 2i checks and clearances.
Get a 2i from DCT
Before it’s published, all GOV.UK content needs to be checked by a DCT content designer to make sure it’s accessible and follows the GOV.UK style guide.
A 2i is a where a DCT content designer reviews the final draft of content in-line with the GOV.UK 2i checklist (opens in new tab) prior to publishing.
A 2i is different to a peer review. Peer reviews can be done at any stage of the drafting process. Content which will be published on GOV.UK should be peer reviewed by a content designer from the DCT.
Get the right clearances
DfE has strict clearance requirements for all GOV.UK publishing. This usually involves clearance from a Deputy Director (DD) and for high profile content, from strategic communications at DfE.
You may need to agree a publication date for certain content. This is to ensure the planning team know when the content will be published and if there are likely to be communication implications, such as media interest or questions.
Find out more on the intranet about DfE clearance processes for GOV.UK content (opens intranet page in new tab). If you do not have access to the DfE intranet, ask a colleague with access to get the information for you.
DCT will publish the content to GOV.UK after 2i checks have been completed and clearances have been confirmed.
Before you make a request for Whitehall publisher
Make sure you’ve spoken to DCT so they can help you decide if a request should be made and what kind of access is needed.
Content designers need to complete GDS training to use Whitehall. To ask for training, submit a request (opens intranet page in new tab). If you do not have access to the DfE intranet, ask a colleague with access to submit a request for you.
Other uses of Whitehall
Whitehall accounts also give individuals access to Integration, the test version of GOV.UK that can be used to prototype content. There are other ways to prototype content, so a Whitehall account cannot be given out just for this use.
To look at data and insight about GOV.UK you can request access to GOV.UK Sign-on. It’s different to a Whitehall publisher account but it still gives you access to:


content data - for analytics about GOV.UK 
feedex data - for user comments on content

Back to ways of working
Interaction Design artefacts and documentation
We use a variety of tools to help us create Interaction Design outputs depending on the purpose, time available and what’s ‘good enough’ to meet the intended purpose
Artefacts
Journey maps
These are created by Interaction Designers in collaboration with Content Designers, User Researchers, Performance Analysts and Service Designers, if available.
All designs should start with a journey map, which meet the needs of the project.
High level understanding
Created with the team and include stakeholders where possible.
Basic boxes and arrows style. Use anything that works as long as it can be saved and edited.
Higher fidelity journey maps can be used if needed by the project or for a different purpose.
Prototypes


concepts for problem solving and discussion; digital sketches, for example, using Figma or Lucidspark
testing interactions and journeys; using the GOV.UK prototype kit and Visual Studio Code

More information on how to prototype and run the prototpye kit
Our documentation
Interaction Design is about more than just prototyping and journey mapping - we have other design outputs which help us to do our work, help with onboarding new team members and to better support or pick up each other’s work.
To track of and document design rationale


design backlog for future consideration
Collaborative Design Review feedback (design decisions made, why and any alternative designs)
design histories
agreed consistent approach to prototype versioning

To help us stay up to date with each other


IxD updates document (updated weekly)
team Trello board for logging and tracking actions from team sessions
team slack channel

To share and work on together


shared, reusable Figma design library
central location for easy access to our IxD and team work
service differences Lucidspark board
behavioural needs Lucidspark board
team foundation activities Lucidspark boards

Back to ways of working
Stages of Interaction Design
Our approach uses a mix of cognitive, strategic and practical processes which we’ve grouped into 5 iterative and looping stages to help keep focus on users and their needs.


    
        
            Understand
            Activities in this phase include:
            
                collaborate and feed into User Research (UR) so we learn how users behave, their needs and pain points and identify any gaps
                observe and scribe user testing
                feed into and understand personas / empathy maps
                analyse / understand user (and business) needs (behavioural, task-based, informational)
                understand the problem
                challenge assumptions
                review existing service(s)
                collaborate with Content Design (CD) and Service Design (SD) to understand and map the As-Is user journey
                create design histories (TBC if IxD or project team task)
                review user stories reflect identified user needs
                stakeholder management (as appropriate)
            
        
        
            Define
  Activities in this phase include:
  
   define the problem (with the team) MVP / what to test / needs to be met
 define the scope
 define the gaps
 challenge assumptions
 define tasks to complete
 create design histories (TBC if IxD task or team task)
 review user stories reflect identified user needs
 stakeholder management (as appropriate)
               
        
        
            Ideate
  Activities in this phase include:
    
 explore concepts, options and journeys
 collaborate with UR to analyse and understand user needs (behaviours, task-based and informational needs) and identify gaps
 collaborate with content design / service design / business analyst / performance analyst on Information Architecture and journeys
 collaborate with devs to understand what’s possible / practical
 map solutions and needs
 mock up the experience (Low / high fidelity sketches / wireframes / prototypes - using the prototype kit)
 Collaborative Design Reviews
 adhere to and champion accessibility standards
 adhere to and champion IxD principles and good practice
 reuse patterns and code as appropriate
 workshops
 documentation (design histories, design rationale, review BA user stories)
 share learnings
 collaborate and feed into User Research so we learn how users behave, their needs and pain points and identify any gaps
 stakeholder management (as appropriate)
 review designs in the repo before they go live with development team
 run design sprint with the whole team to co-create ideas/solutions
  
        
        
            Refine
  Activities in this phase include:
    
   collaborate and feed into User Research so we learn how users behave, their needs and pain points and identify any gaps
 evaluate and evolve / iterate prototypes / journeys based on UR or design review
 Collaborative Design Reviews
 collaborate on dev build
 support accessibility testing
 documentation (design histories)
 share learnings
 stakeholder management (as appropriate)
  
        
        
            Iterate
  Activities in this phase include:
    
   celebrate successes
 support UR
 learn and iterate cycle
 documentation
